===========================Arrays=========================================================================
An array is a collection of elements of similar data type under a single name stored in contiguous memory 
locations and accessed using an index.

Characterstics of an array : 
1: Same Data Type
2: Contigeous Memory allocation
3: Fixed Size
4: Zero Based Indexing

We can create an array in three ways in C# .....

1: When we know the size but don't know the values yet then we use.
int[] arr = new int[5];

2: When the values are already known then we use.
string[] months =
{
    "Jan",
    "Feb",
    "Mar"
};

3: 
int[] arr = new int[]
{
    10,
    20,
    30
};
At first glance it seems unnecessary. But here's where it becomes useful.

Scenario 1: Passing an array directly to a method :
static void Print(int[] numbers)
{
    foreach(int number in numbers){
        Console.WriteLine(number);
    }
}
Print(new int[]{10, 20, 30});

Scenario 2: Conditional assignment :
int[] arr;
if(condition)
{
    arr = new int[] {1,2,3};
}
else
{
    arr = new int[] {4,5,6};
}

Why do scripting languages allow mixed-type arrays while languages like C# usually require the same data type ?
First, a small correction:
It's not "scripting language vs programming language."
There are scripting languages that support typed arrays, and programming languages that support heterogeneous collections.

The real difference is usually:
Dynamically typed languages vs Statically typed languages.

JavaScript :
let arr = [10, "Piyush", true, 5.6];
Perfectly valid.

C#
int[] arr = {10, "Piyush", true};
❌ Compile-time error.
Why?
Let's think like a computer.

C# 
Suppose :
int[] arr = {10,20,30};
The compiler knows
Every element = int
↓
Every element = 4 bytes
↓
Memory layout :
10
20
30

This allows:
Very fast indexing
Less memory
Compile-time checking
CPU optimizations

JavaScript 
let arr = [10,"Piyush",true];
Now the engine cannot assume
Index 0 → int
Index 1 → string
Index 2 → bool

Internally it's more like
Reference
↓
Object
↓
Actual Value

Every element carries type information. That flexibility costs :
More memory
More runtime checks
More complex optimizations

So what is the biggest reason?
Not security.
The biggest reason is performance and predictability.

In C#, arrays are commonly categorized into 4 main types.
| Type                                                 | Syntax                   | Description                                                                              |
| ---------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Single-Dimensional Array**                      | `int[]`                  | Stores elements in one row 
(linear collection).                                          |
| **2. Multidimensional Array**                        | `int[,]`, `int[,,]`      | Stores elements in two or more dimensions (rectangular table).                           |
| **3. Jagged Array**                                  | `int[][]`                | An array of arrays where each inner array can have a different length.                   |
| **4. Jagged Multidimensional Array** *(less common)* | `int[][,]` or `int[,][]` | A combination of jagged and multidimensional arrays. Used only in specialized scenarios. |

⭐ One thing you may not know :
An array can store any data type, not just primitive types.
For example:

string[] names;
Student[] students;
Employee[] employees;
object[] items;

So int[] is just one example. The element type can be any valid C# type, including your own custom classes. This is why arrays are a very general feature in C#.

================ Some common properties and methods .......................

In C#, not everything that looks like an array method actually belongs to the array object.
There are three categories:

Properties of an array (Length, Rank)
Instance methods inherited from System.Array (Clone(), CopyTo(), etc.)
Static methods of the Array class (Sort(), Reverse(), IndexOf(), etc.)

1 : int[] arr = {10,20,30,40}; Console.WriteLine(arr.Length); 
Returns the total number of elements in the array.

2: int[,] matrix = new int[3,4]; Console.WriteLine(matrix.Rank);
Returns the number of dimensions of an array.

3: int[,] matrix = new int[3,4]; Console.WriteLine(matrix.GetLength(1));
Returns the length of a specific dimension.

4: int[] arr = {5,2,8,1}; Array.Sort(arr); 

5: int[] arr = {5,2,8,1}; Array.Reverse(arr); 
Reverses the order of elements in an array.

6: int[] arr = {10,20,30}; Console.WriteLine(Array.IndexOf(arr,30));
Returns the index of the first occurrence of an element.

7: int[] arr = {10,20,10,30}; Console.WriteLine(Array.LastIndexOf(arr,10));
Returns the index of the last occurrence of an element.

8: int[] source = {1,2,3}; int[] destination = new int[3]; Array.Copy(source,destination,3);
Copies elements from one array to another.

9: int[] arr = {10,20,30}; int[] copy = (int[])arr.Clone();
Creates a shallow copy of the entire array.

10: int[] arr = {10,20,30}; Array.Clear(arr,0,2);
Sets a range of array elements to their default values.

11: bool found = Array.Exists(arr, x => x > 20);
Checks whether any element satisfies a condition.

12: int value = Array.Find(arr, x => x > 20);
Returns the first matching element.

13: int[] even = Array.FindAll(arr, x => x % 2 == 0);
Returns all matching elements.

14: Array.BinarySearch(arr,30); 
Searches a sorted array efficiently.

⭐ One thing many C# developers don't know
Notice these two calls:

arr.Clone();
and
Array.Sort(arr);

Why aren't they both written the same way ?
Because:
Clone() is an instance method inherited by every array object from System.Array, so you call it on the array itself.
Sort(), Reverse(), Copy(), IndexOf(), and many others are static methods of the Array class. They operate on arrays that you pass as arguments rather than on a single array instance.

This distinction between instance members and static utility methods is common throughout the .NET Base Class Library and is worth understanding early.
